.TH "TEMPORAL.ZONEDDATETIME.FROM" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from \- Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from()
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from()\f[B]\f[R] static method
creates a new \f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] object from another
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] object, an object with date, time, and
time zone properties, or an RFC 9557 string.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(info)
Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(info, options)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]info\f[R]
One of the following:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
A \f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] instance, which creates a copy of
the instance.
.IP \(bu 2
An RFC 9557 format string containing a date, optionally a time,
optionally an offset, a time zone annotation, and optionally a calendar.
.IP \(bu 2
An object containing properties that are accepted by either
\f[CR]Temporal.PlainDate.from()\f[R] (\f[CR]calendar\f[R],
\f[CR]era\f[R], \f[CR]eraYear\f[R], \f[CR]year\f[R], \f[CR]month\f[R],
\f[CR]monthCode\f[R], \f[CR]day\f[R]) or
\f[CR]Temporal.PlainTime.from()\f[R] (\f[CR]hour\f[R],
\f[CR]minute\f[R], \f[CR]second\f[R], \f[CR]millisecond\f[R],
\f[CR]microsecond\f[R], \f[CR]nanosecond\f[R]).
The info should explicitly specify a year (as \f[CR]year\f[R] or as
\f[CR]era\f[R] and \f[CR]eraYear\f[R]), a month (as \f[CR]month\f[R] or
\f[CR]monthCode\f[R]), and a day; others are optional and will be set to
their default values.
The following properties should be provided too:
.RS 2
.TP
\f[B]timeZone\f[R]
Either a string or a \f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] instance
representing the time zone to use.
If a \f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] instance, its time zone is used.
If a string, it can be a named time zone identifier, an offset time zone
identifier, or a date\-time string containing a time zone identifier or
an offset (see time zones and offsets for more information).
The time properties are interpreted in this time zone.
.TP
\f[B]offset\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
An offset string, in the same format as the RFC 9557 offset but with
optional seconds and subsecond components
(\f[CR]±HH:mm:ss.sssssssss\f[R]), representing the offset from UTC.
If omitted, it will be calculated from the time zone and the date\-time.
\f[CR]\(dqZ\(dq\f[R] is not allowed.
.RE
.RE
.TP
\f[B]options\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
An object containing some or all of the following properties (in the
order they are retrieved and validated):
.RS
.TP
\f[B]disambiguation\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
What to do if the local date\-time is ambiguous in the given time zone
(there are more than one instants with such local time, or the local
time does not exist).
Possible values are \f[CR]\(dqcompatible\(dq\f[R],
\f[CR]\(dqearlier\(dq\f[R], \f[CR]\(dqlater\(dq\f[R], and
\f[CR]\(dqreject\(dq\f[R].
Defaults to \f[CR]\(dqcompatible\(dq\f[R].
For more information about these values, see ambiguity and gaps from
local time to UTC time.
.TP
\f[B]offset\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
What to do if the offset is explicitly provided in \f[CR]info\f[R] but
the offset is invalid for the given time zone in the given local time.
Possible values are \f[CR]\(dquse\(dq\f[R], \f[CR]\(dqignore\(dq\f[R],
\f[CR]\(dqreject\(dq\f[R], and \f[CR]\(dqprefer\(dq\f[R].
Defaults to \f[CR]\(dqreject\(dq\f[R].
For more information about these values, see offset ambiguity.
.TP
\f[B]overflow\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
A string specifying the behavior when a date component is out of range
(when using the object \f[CR]info\f[R]).
Possible values are:
.RS
.TP
\f[B]\(dqconstrain\(dq\f[R] (default)
The date component is clamped to the valid range.
.TP
\f[B]\(dqreject\(dq\f[R]
A \f[CR]RangeError\f[R] is thrown if the date component is out of range.
.RE
.RE
.SS Return value
A new \f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] object, representing the date
and time specified by \f[CR]info\f[R] in the specified
\f[CR]calendar\f[R] and \f[CR]timeZone\f[R].
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]TypeError\f[R]
Thrown in one of the following cases:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]info\f[R] is not an object or a string.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]options\f[R] is not an object or \f[CR]undefined\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
The provided properties are insufficient to unambiguously determine a
date.
You usually need to provide a \f[CR]year\f[R] (or \f[CR]era\f[R] and
\f[CR]eraYear\f[R]), a \f[CR]month\f[R] (or \f[CR]monthCode\f[R]), and a
\f[CR]day\f[R].
.RE
.TP
\f[B]RangeError\f[R]
Thrown in one of the following cases:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
The provided properties that specify the same component are
inconsistent.
.IP \(bu 2
The provided non\-numerical properties are not valid; for example, if
\f[CR]monthCode\f[R] is never a valid month code in this calendar.
.IP \(bu 2
The provided numerical properties are out of range, and
\f[CR]options.overflow\f[R] is set to \f[CR]\(dqreject\(dq\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
The wall\-clock time is ambiguous in the time zone, and
\f[CR]options.disambiguation\f[R] is set to \f[CR]\(dqreject\(dq\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
The info is not in the representable range, which is ±10\(ha8 days, or
about ±273,972.6 years, from the Unix epoch.
.RE
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Creating a ZonedDateTime from an object
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// Year + month + day + hour + minute + second\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] zdt = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from({
  timeZone: \(dqAmerica/New_York\(dq,
  year: 2021,
  month: 7,
  day: 1,
  hour: 12,
  minute: 34,
  second: 56,
});
console.log(zdt.toString()); \f[I]// \(dq2021\-07\-01T12:34:56\-04:00[America/New_York]\(dq\f[R]
.EE
.SS Creating a ZonedDateTime from a string
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] zdt = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq2021\-07\-01T12:34:56\-04:00[America/New_York]\(dq,
);
console.log(zdt.toLocaleString()); \f[I]// \(dq7/1/2021, 12:34:56 PM EDT\(dq (assuming en\-US locale)\f[R]

\f[I]// Time given as UTC, and converted to local\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] zdt2 = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq2021\-07\-01T12:34:56Z[America/New_York]\(dq,
);
console.log(zdt2.toString()); \f[I]// \(dq2021\-07\-01T08:34:56\-04:00[America/New_York]\(dq\f[R]
.EE
.SS Creating a ZonedDateTime from an ISO 8601 / RFC 3339 string
Note that \f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from()\f[R] rejects ISO 8601
strings, which do not include a time zone identifier.
This is to ensure that the time zone is always known and can be used to
derive different offsets as the local time changes.
.PP
If you want to parse an ISO 8601 string, first construct a
\f[CR]Temporal.Instant\f[R] object and then convert it to a
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] object.
You can provide any time zone, even if it doesn\(cqt match the offset
originally given in the string, and the local time will be adjusted
accordingly.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] isoString = \(dq2021\-07\-01T12:34:56+02:00\(dq;
\f[B]const\f[R] instant = Temporal.Instant.from(isoString);
\f[B]const\f[R] zdt = instant.toZonedDateTimeISO(\(dqAmerica/New_York\(dq);
console.log(zdt.toString()); \f[I]// \(dq2021\-07\-01T06:34:56\-04:00[America/New_York]\(dq\f[R]
.EE
.SS Local time disambiguation
See ambiguity and gaps from local time to UTC time for an introduction
to this situation.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] localTimeNotExist = \(dq2024\-03\-10T02:05:00[America/New_York]\(dq;
\f[I]// For non\-existent times, \(dqcompatible\(dq is equivalent to \(dqlater\(dq\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] zdt = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(localTimeNotExist);
console.log(zdt.toString()); \f[I]// \(dq2024\-03\-10T03:05:00\-04:00[America/New_York]\(dq\f[R]

\f[B]const\f[R] zdt2 = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(localTimeNotExist, {
  disambiguation: \(dqearlier\(dq,
});
console.log(zdt2.toString()); \f[I]// \(dq2024\-03\-10T01:05:00\-05:00[America/New_York]\(dq\f[R]

\f[B]const\f[R] localTimeAmbiguous = \(dq2024\-11\-03T01:05:00[America/New_York]\(dq;
\f[I]// For ambiguous times, \(dqcompatible\(dq is equivalent to \(dqearlier\(dq\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] zdt3 = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(localTimeAmbiguous);
console.log(zdt3.toString()); \f[I]// \(dq2024\-11\-03T01:05:00\-04:00[America/New_York]\(dq\f[R]

\f[B]const\f[R] zdt4 = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(localTimeAmbiguous, {
  disambiguation: \(dqlater\(dq,
});
console.log(zdt4.toString()); \f[I]// \(dq2024\-11\-03T01:05:00\-05:00[America/New_York]\(dq\f[R]
.EE
.SS Resolving offset ambiguity
See offset ambiguity for an introduction to this situation.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] offsetAmbiguous = \(dq2019\-12\-23T12:00:00\-02:00[America/Sao_Paulo]\(dq;

Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(offsetAmbiguous);
\f[I]// RangeError: date\-time can\(aqt be represented in the given time zone\f[R]
Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(offsetAmbiguous, { offset: \(dquse\(dq }).toString();
\f[I]// \(dq2019\-12\-23T11:00:00\-03:00[America/Sao_Paulo]\(dq\f[R]
Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(offsetAmbiguous, { offset: \(dqignore\(dq }).toString();
\f[I]// \(dq2019\-12\-23T12:00:00\-03:00[America/Sao_Paulo]\(dq\f[R]
.EE
.PP
For more examples, especially regarding different calendars and overflow
settings, see \f[CR]Temporal.PlainDate.from()\f[R] and
\f[CR]Temporal.PlainTime.from()\f[R].
.SH SEE ALSO
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime()\f[R]
